                    <h3>International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS) and Cryptocurrencies</h3>
                    <p>The International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS) provide a global framework for financial reporting, which is pertinent to crypto accounting. While there is no specific IFRS standard dedicated solely to cryptocurrencies, several standards offer guidance on their treatment:</p>

                    <ul>
                        <li><p><strong>IAS 38 – Intangible Assets : </strong>Cryptocurrencies are often classified as intangible assets under IAS 38, as they lack physical substance and are identifiable non-monetary assets. This classification impacts how financial statements recognize, measure, and disclose cryptocurrencies.</p></li>
                        <li><p><strong>IAS 2 – Inventories : </strong>For entities that hold cryptocurrencies for sale in the ordinary course of business, such as crypto traders or brokers, IAS 2 may apply, treating these assets as inventories.</p></li>
                        <li><p><strong>IFRS 13 – Fair Value Measuremen : </strong>This standard provides guidance on measuring the fair value of assets, including cryptocurrencies, which is essential given their market volatility.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Adhering to these standards ensures that financial statements accurately reflect the value and performance of cryptocurrency holdings, providing stakeholders with reliable information.</p>
